This methodology has the potential to become a tool to be applied in any UGGp willing to study the spatial distribution of the management strategies, activity impacts and benefits on the sustainable development of the territories through time. In order to identify and discuss the territorial dynamics, the presence and distribution of the UGGp concept and their activities, four GeoLAC UGGps were selected (Araripe UGGp, Brazil; Grutas del Palacio UGGp, Uruguay; Comarca Minera UGGp and Mixteca Alta UGGp, Mexico). Workshops took place in all territories including activities of participative cartography, with the direct involvement of representative groups of local inhabitants. The following aspects were considered for the construction of maps:

                           (1)

areas, sites and/or corridors with high tourism influence;


                           (2)

areas, sites and/or corridors with greatest economic benefits;


                           (3)

areas, sites and/or corridors less engaged with the geopark concept and activities;


                           (4)

areas, sites and/or corridors with more educational activities identified;


                           (5)

areas, sites and/or corridors environmentally more preserved;


                           (6)

areas, sites and/or corridors of local and sustainable production identified;


                           (7)

areas, sites and/or corridors related with well-being and healthy lifestyles;


                           (8)

areas, sites and/or corridors with identified conservation and natural restoration policies;


                           (9)

areas, sites and/or corridors more affected due the climate change;


                           (10)

areas, sites and/or corridors polluted;


                           (11)

areas, sites and/or corridors with highest need of clean water and sanitization;


                           (12)

areas, sites and/or corridors with more needs of security and peace;


                           (13)

areas, sites and/or corridors of women cooperatives created/promoted under the auspice of the management structure;


                           (14)

areas, sites and/or corridors with waste management initiatives;


                           (15)

areas, sites and/or corridors that promotes social equity and justice;


                           (16)

areas, sites and/or corridors with educational potential not considered in the master plan;


                           (17)

areas, sites and/or corridors with touristic potential not considered into the master plan;


                           (18)

areas, sites and/or corridors with environmental conservation that requires management structure action;


                           (19)

areas, sites and/or corridors with sustainable production potential not considered by the management structure;


                           (20)

areas, sites and/or corridors for water environment conservation, sustainable initiatives and/or ecological restoration;


                           (21)

areas, sites and/or corridors with sustainable community infrastructures and services for development;


                           (22)

areas, sites and/or corridors with more community participation and solidarity.
